        <section class="article-information-group toggle-content is-visible" id="article-information">

			
							<section class="article-information abstract">
					<h2>Abstract</h2>
					The primary objective of this paper is to provide information about minorities (blacks, Hispanics and Native Americans)in economics, at various stages in the education pipeline, and in the labor market. Despite sustained increases in the numbers and percentages of minorities earning bachelors degrees and Ph.D.s, the absolute numbers remain very small--only about 36 new Ph.D.s per year, including permanent residents. Minority economists are relatively underrepresented on four-year college faculties and in government employment. The paper also discusses activities by the AEA's committee on minority groups, aimed at increasing minority representation in the profession.				</section>
			
							<section class="article-information citation">
					<h2>Citation</h2>
